Harry Lu

January 29, 2019

Population standardized skewness

\[\text{sk}=\text{E}\left[\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^3\right]=\frac{\text{E}\left[(x-\mu)^3\right]}{\sigma^3}\]

Population standardized kurtosis

\[\text{kur}=\text{E}\left[\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^4\right]=\frac{\text{E}\left[(x-\mu)^4\right]}{\sigma^4}\]

Normal distribution: \(\text{sk}=0\) and \(\text{kur}=3\)

t distribution with degree of freedom \(\text{df}\): \(\text{sk}=0\) and \(\text{kur}=3+\frac{6}{\text{df}-4}\)

\[\hat{\text{sk}}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{x_i-\bar{x}}{s}\right)^3\]

\[\hat{\text{kur}}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{x_i-\bar{x}}{s}\right)^4\]

e.g. Dow Jones INDEX: \(\hat{\text{sk}}\approx0\), \(\hat{\text{kur}}\approx14\), so \(14=3+\frac{6}{\text{df}-4}\), gives \(\hat{\text{df}}\approx4.5\)

Formal Test for Normality

\[\text{JB}=n\left[\frac{(\hat{\text{sk}})^2}{6}+\frac{(\hat{\text{kur}}-3)^2}{24}\right] \xrightarrow{d} \chi^2_2\]

Shapiro-Wilk test: based on the correlation between \(X_{(i)}\) and \(\text{E}(X_{(i)})\)

\(\text{E}(X_{(i)}) \leftrightarrow \Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{i}{n+1}\right),\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{i-\frac{1}{2}}{n}\right)\)

Checking for t-distributed Returns

Location-scale Student’s t-model: \(y\sim a+bt_{(\text{df})}\), where \(a\) is location parameter and \(b\) is scale parameter

When \(\text{df}=\infty\), \(t_{(\infty)}=N(0,1)\), \(y\sim N(a,b^2)\)

When \(\text{df}>1\), \(y\) has mean \(a\)

When \(\text{df}>2\), \(y\) has standard deviation \(b\cdot\sqrt{\frac{\text{df}}{\text{df}-2}}\)

Let \(F_{\text{df}}(t)\) be the cdf of \(t_{(\text{df})}\)

Compare \(X_{(i)}\) with \(F_{\text{df}}^{-1}\left(\frac{i}{n+1}\right)\), if the model holds \(X_{(i)}\approx a+b\cdot F_{\text{df}}^{-1}\left(\frac{i}{n+1}\right)\)

Get \(\text{df}\) to use by \(\hat{\text{df}}\) where \(\left(\hat{a},\hat{b},\hat{\text{df}}\right)\) is the maximum likelihood estimate of \((a,b,\text{df})\)

e.g. \(n=3\), \(\frac{i}{n+1}=0.25,0.50,0.75\) as \(i=1,2,3\)

  • \(X_{(1)}=\mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{3+1}\right)=\mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-1}(0.25)\)
  • \(X_{(2)}=\mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{2}{3+1}\right)=\mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-1}(0.50)=\mu\)
  • \(X_{(3)}=\mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{3}{3+1}\right)=\mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-1}(0.75)\)

\(X_{(i)}\) should be approximately the \(\frac{i}{n+1}\) - quantile of the distribution. Or \(\text{E}[y_{(i)}]\approx\mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{i-\frac{1}{2}}{n}\right)\)

Time Series Methods

A time series is a collection of observed random variables indexed by time. A stochastic process is a model for a time series.

Discrete time series: \(X_t\) is the variable at time \(t\)

  • e.g. \(X_1,X_2,X_3,\cdots\)
  • e.g. \(X_0,X_1,X_2,\cdots\)
  • e.g. \(X_{-2},X_{-1},X_0,X_1,X_2,\cdots\)

Assume the time series is “systematic” to have a small collection of parameters to be estimated.

(I) Strictly Stationary

Assume \(X_1,\cdots,X_n\) has the same distribution as \(X_{1+k},\cdots,X_{n+k}\) for all \(k\)

e.g. \((X_2,X_7,X_{20})\) has the same distribution as \((X_{45},X_{50},X_{63})\). Also, \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) and \(X_3\), etc. all have the same distribution

(II) Weakly Stationary

  1. \(\text{E}(X_t)=\mu\) for all \(t\)
    • e.g. \(\text{E}(X_8)=\text{E}(X_{20})\)
  2. \(\text{Var}(X_t)=\sigma^2\) for all \(t\)
    • e.g. \(\text{Var}(X_8)=\text{Var}(X_{20})\)
  3. \(\text{Cov}(X_t,X_u)=\gamma(|t-u|)\)
    • e.g. \(\text{Cov}(X_8)=\text{Cov}(X_{20})\)

\(\gamma(h)\) is called the auto-covariance function

\(\gamma(0)=\text{Cov}(X_t,X_t)=\text{Var}(X_t)=\sigma^2\)

The auto-correlation function \(\rho(h)\) gives \(\text{Corr}(X_t,X_u)=\rho(|t-u|)\)

\[\rho(h)=\frac{\gamma(h)}{\sigma^2}=\frac{\gamma(h)}{\gamma(0)}\]

Strictly Stationary –> Weakly Stationary

Suppose \(X_1,X_2,\cdots\) independent. \(X_i\sim N(0,1)\), where \(i\) is odder number. \(X_j\sim \sqrt{\frac{\text{df}-2}{\text{df}}}\cdot t_{(\text{df})}\), where \(j\) is even number (\(\text{df}>2\)).

(III) Weak White Noise

  1. \(\text{E}(X_t)=\mu\) for all \(t\)
  2. \(\text{Var}(X_t)=\sigma^2\) for all \(t\)
  3. \(\text{Cov}(X_t,X_u)=0\) for \(t\neq u\)

So \(\gamma(0)=\sigma^2\), \(\gamma(h)=0\) for \(h\neq0\)

and \(\rho(0)=1\), \(\rho(h)=0\) for \(h\neq0\)

Weak White Noise –> Weakly Stationary

(IV) \(i.i.d.\) White Noise

Weak white noise where variables are \(i.i.d.\)

–> Strictly stationary

–> Weak White Noise
